    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>The Schiff's reagent is used to test the presence of <strong>aldehyde</strong> functional groups.</p>\n<p>Let's analyse each option:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><p><strong>Option A:</strong> $-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\mathrm{OH}$ (<strong>Primary alcohol</strong>). Schiff's reagent <strong>does not</strong> give a pink colour with alcohols.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Option B:</strong> $-\\mathrm{COOH}$ (<strong>Carboxylic acid</strong>). Schiff's reagent <strong>does not</strong> give a pink colour with carboxylic acids.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Option C:</strong> $-\\mathrm{CHO}$ (<strong>Aldehyde</strong>). Schiff's reagent <strong>gives</strong> a pink or magenta colour with aldehydes.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>Option D:</strong> $-\\mathrm{CO}-$ (<strong>Ketone</strong>). Schiff's reagent <strong>does not</strong> give a pink colour with ketones.</p></li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Conclusion:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The functional group that forms a pink colour with Schiff’s reagent is the <strong>aldehyde group</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Final Answer:</strong>  </p>\n<p><strong>Option C:</strong> $-\\mathrm{CHO}$</p>",
